Long ago, a beautiful goddess appeared from “Sugata Pond” in Nikaidō, {{ill|lt=Tenri City|Q502196|WD=Q502196}}. She rested for a while in Kagurada in Hachijō-chō, Yamatokōriyama City, and then went westward and took up residence there. Overnight, the place became a dense pine grove, and people began to call the area “Ichiya-matsu” (One-Night Pine). Thus, the present Sugata Shrine—also known as “Ichiya-matsu Tenjin” or “Hachijō Tenjin Shrine”—came to be enshrined there<ref>From the shrine notice board</ref>. The {{ill||lt=Meiji Jinja Shiryō|UNKNOWN}} records: “The Saho River flows to the west, overlooking the banks of Sugata Pond. In the *Horigawa Hyakushu*<ref group="note">A poetry anthology from the late Heian period, likely compiled around the 2nd year of Chōji (1105).</ref>, it is written: ‘The lotus leaves on Sugata Pond, where the maiden dwells, bloom with a gentle heart.’ From this one may know that it was a place of scenic beauty.”

=== Overview ===
The enshrined deity is Sugata-hiko-no-Mikoto. There is also a theory that the deity is {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Mahitotsu-no-Kami|Q10016750|WD=Q10016750}}, an ancestor of Sugata-hiko-no-Mikoto and regarded as a god of blacksmithing<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/815494/1/11 |title=Shingi Shiryō |access-date=2024-4-24}}</ref>. However, the {{ill|lt=Jinja Meisaichō|Q11590704|WD=Q11590704}} of {{ill|lt=Heguri District|Q11483501|WD=Q11483501}} (Hachijō Village in the {{ill||lt=Meiji period|UNKNOWN}} was under the jurisdiction of Heguri District and {{ill|lt=Ikoma District|Q971003|WD=Q971003}}, and was incorporated into {{ill|lt=Kōriyama Town (Nara Prefecture)||WD=|lt=Kōriyama Town}} in 1953) records Sugata-hiko-no-Mikoto as the enshrined deity<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://meta01.library.pref.nara.jp/opac/repository/repo/69/ |title=Heguri District Shrine Registry |access-date=2024-4-23}}</ref>. Sugata-hiko-no-Mikoto is the ancestor of the Sugata clan, and the {{ill|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|Q1045362|WD=Q1045362}} states: “The Sugata no Obito are descendants of {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Mahitotsu-no-Kami|Q10016750|WD=Q10016750|lt=Ame-no-Kushi-mahito-tsu-no-Mikoto}}.”

Before the early modern period, the shrine was also called Hachijō Tenjin Shrine or Ichiya-matsu Tenjin, and it enshrined {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|WD=Q382005}}. A legend tells of a miracle in which a pine tree grew overnight, and part of the bark of the Ichiya Pine is {{ill|lt=dedicated|Q2601788|WD=Q2601788}} in the {{ill|lt=worship hall|Q3125745|WD=Q3125745}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://yamatotk.web.fc2.com/kouriyama/sugata.htm |title=Sugata Shrine |access-date=2024-4-23}}</ref>. A stone lantern from the 5th year of {{ill|lt=Genna (Japan)|Q635245|WD=Q635245|lt=Genna}} (1619) bears the inscription “Ichiya-matsu Kinrin-gū,” suggesting the existence of a {{ill|lt=jingū-ji|Q1074971|WD=Q1074971}} called Ichiya-matsu Kinrin-ji. Its location is estimated to have been west of Kasuga Shrine in Nikaidō Kita-Sugata-chō, {{ill|lt=Tenri City|Q502196|WD=Q502196}}<ref group="note">Originally, “it was probably dedicated to Ame-no-Kushi-hitotsu-no-Mikoto” (from *Tenri City History*).</ref><ref name=":01">Tenri City History, Volume 1</ref>.

The {{ill|lt=main hall|Q2044994|WD=Q2044994}} is built in the {{ill|lt=Kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|WD=Q3193781}} style, with a {{ill|lt=heiden|Q3076699|WD=Q3076699}} installed between it and the {{ill|lt=worship hall|Q3125745|WD=Q3125745}}. In front of the main hall stands a stone lantern inscribed “Before the Deity of Tenmangū,” indicating that the shrine was associated with {{ill|lt=Tenjin worship|Q66890725|WD=Q66890725}}.

It is also thought to form a pair with {{ill|lt=Sugata-hime Shrine|Q134893097|WD=Q134893097}}, another Shikinaisha of Soekami District located in Tsutsui-chō, Yamatokōriyama City (enshrining Sugata-hime-no-Mikoto and Ame-no-Kushi-mahito-tsu-no-Mikoto, two deities<ref>According to *Tokusen Shinmeichō* and the National Diet Library Search “Research on Shikinaisha, Vol. 2.”</ref>)<ref group="note">However, the Soekami District Shrine Registry lists only one deity: Izunome-no-Kami.</ref>.

The enshrined deities of {{ill|lt=Sugata Shrine (Ono City)||WD=|lt=Sugata Shrine}} (a Shikinaisha) in {{ill|lt=Ono City|Q911717|WD=Q911717}}, {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|WD=Q130290}}, and {{ill|lt=Sugata Shrine (Ōmihachiman City)||WD=|lt=Sugata Shrine}} (a Shikinaisha) in {{ill|lt=Ōmihachiman City|Q385461|WD=Q385461}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358}}, are Ame-no-Mahitotsu-no-Kami.

=== Auxiliary shrines ===
* Itsukushima Shrine (Deity: {{ill||lt=Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|UNKNOWN}})

* Kasuga Shrine (Deity: {{ill||lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|UNKNOWN}})

* Kōtaijingū (Deity: {{ill|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|Q455602|WD=Q455602}})

* Haraedo Shrine (Deity: {{ill|lt=Haraedo Ōkami|Q11588504|WD=Q11588504}})

=== Annual festival ===
It was formerly held on October 28, but is now held on October 15.

It is jointly celebrated by Minami-Sugata, Kita-Sugata, Hachijō, Chōan-ji, Miyadō, Nukatabe, Nishimura, and other areas. During the {{ill|lt=procession|Q11561919|WD=Q11561919}} of the hosting household, it is customary for the Sugata clan of Minami-Sugata to proceed first<ref name=":01" />.

